 "bio": {
  "extract": "Paul Jackson Pollock was an American painter. A major figure in the abstract expressionist movement, he was widely noticed for his \"drip technique\" of pouring or splashing liquid household paint onto a horizontal surface, enabling him to view and paint his canvases from all angles. It was called all-over painting and action painting, because Pollock covered the entire canvas and used the force of his whole body to paint, often in a frenetic dancing style. This extreme form of abstraction divided critics: some praised the immediacy of the creation, while others derided the random effects.",
  "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackson_Pollock"
 },
